<p><strong>SHURE PG48&#160;</strong></p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgzi01oKaN1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p><a href="http://www.shure.com/idc/groups/public/documents/webcontent/us_pro_pg48_specsheet.pdf">http://www.shure.com/idc/groups/public/documents/webcontent/us_pro_pg48_specsheet.pdf</a></p>
<p>Dynamic vocal microphone with on/off switch, XLR connection, and its  polar pattern is cardioid.  It responds to frequencies between 70-15000  Hz:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgzi8jPI6d1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>Price: 30-50USD</p>
<p>History:  I couldn&#8217;t find too much about these besides that they&#8217;re  the cheaper version of the SM58 which has been the industry standard for  this type of vocal microphone since 1966!  (Sadly they don&#8217;t even have  when the PG48 came out on the Shure timeline of mics made)</p>
<p><strong>SHURE 55SH Series II Unidyne Vocal Microphone</strong></p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgzj55gdY51qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p><a href="http://www.fullcompass.com/common/files/455-Shure55SHIISpecSheet.pdf">http://www.fullcompass.com/common/files/455-Shure55SHIISpecSheet.pdf</a></p>
<p>Dynamic vocal microphone with on/off switch, XLR connection, and its  polar pattern is cardioid.  It responds to frequencies between 50-15000  Hz:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgzi9qNevn1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>Price: 175USD</p>
<p>History: The look is iconic!  The first version (SH55) was made in  1939 - <a href="http://shure.custhelp.com/ci/fattach/get/19788/.%C2%A0">http://shure.custhelp.com/ci/fattach/get/19788/. </a> There :).</p>
<p>Shure Green Bullet 520DX Dynamic Harmonica Microphone</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgzjmekUYA1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p><a href="http://www.shure.com/idc/groups/public/documents/webcontent/us_pro_520dx_ug.pdf">http://www.shure.com/idc/groups/public/documents/webcontent/us_pro_520dx_ug.pdf</a></p>
<p>Dynamic microphone with crystal diaphragm used primarily by harmonica (harp) players that gives a lovely blues sound to the instrument.  1/4&#8221; jack connection and its polar pattern is omnidirectional - of course its only got one side open to sound so&#8230; Frequency response is between 100-5000Hz.</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgzjjuGb3y1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>Price: 120USD</p>
<p>History: According to Shure, if you have a harmonica and you like blues, this is the microphone to use with it!</p>
<p>These again were the dynamic microphones - I&#8217;ll go into the others that we have in Part III!  If you&#8217;d like me to look further into any of these mics, please let me know. </p>
