</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3525431464"  data-post-id='3525431464' data-root-id='3525431464' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='i3qUK2K9' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.87815600 1406042024986936357' data-json='{"post-id":"3525431464","root-id":"3525431464","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"i3qUK2K9","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.87815600 1406042024986936357","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223525431464\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223525431464\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022i3qUK2K9\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.87815600 1406042024986936357\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">Thirteenth Ham lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>Well, after spending WAY too much time on reactance and impedance&#8230;we&#8217;re onto other components of a circuit!  And to preface this section, I will be making a chart of how ac/dc current/voltage are affected by capacitors/resistors/inducers in the next couple of days.</p>
<p>Our starting sentence:</p>
<p>"There are other types of components whose response depends on the polarity and value of voltage and current.  <em>We&#8217;ll explore these with the different components I imagine.</em> These are usually constructed from a semiconductor material.&#8221;</p>
<p><strong>SEMICONDUCTOR:</strong> Material that doesn&#8217;t conduct electricity as well as a conductor but is also a pretty poor insulator.  The jack of all trades?</p>
<p>You can DOPE the semiconductor (silicon) with certain impurities (ion implantation) that end up changing how it conducts current.  And depending on <em>how</em> you dope it, you end up with either <strong>N(egative)-type</strong> or <strong>P(ositive)-type</strong> materials. </p>
<ul><li>If it is a <em>pure</em> semiconductor with no doping, it is an <strong>intrinsic semiconductor</strong>.  </li>
<li>If it is lightly doped and stays closer to a semiconductor, it&#8217;s known as an <strong>extrinsic semiconductor</strong>.  </li>
<li>If you dope it such that you end up with a material that&#8217;s more of a  conductor - it&#8217;s called a <strong>degenerate semiconductor</strong>.  </li>
</ul><p>Surprisingly, the wikis for these are pretty well written.  So I&#8217;ll direct you to those, but here&#8217;s a short summary of it a slightly more indepth view on the above terms:</p>
<ol><li><strong>Doping</strong> is making an intrinsic semiconductor into an extrinsic one.  This involves putting atoms of element X on the pure semiconductor so as to encourage either more (extrinsic) or even more (degenerate) conduction of electricity.</li>
<li><strong>N-type semiconductors</strong> are extrinsic.  The doping atoms provide extra conduction electrons to the semiconductor.  This creates an excess of negative (n-type) electron charge carriers.</li>
<li><strong>P-type semiconductors</strong> are made by doping atoms that increase the number of free charge carriers.  Or put in another way, increase the number of positive atoms that can accept electrons and therefore increase the number of holes in the conductor for more electrons to come through.</li>
</ol><p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgn76qy7PE1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>On the left, silicon is our intrinsic semiconductor.  In the middle is our n-type semiconductor where phosphorus has donated extra electrons to silicon.  On the right is our p-type semiconductor where boron has created more holes.  More electrons = more flow.  More holes = more overall positive charge = more attraction of electrons to those holes = more flow.</p>
<ol></ol><p>So if we think way back to how electrons move through a circuit, I talked about the marble in a tube idea.  N-type conductors is like adding more marbles to increase conductance.  P-type conductors is like taking out more marbles - thus making holes - thus allowing the marbles above to fall down at a more rapid rate.</p>
<p>Now. If you put N- and P-type materials together, the result is a <strong>PN junction </strong>that conducts better in one direction than the other.  More specifics next article!</p>
<p>Basic explanation from someone else:</p>
<p><a href="http://electronics.howstuffworks.com/diode.htm">http://electronics.howstuffworks.com/diode.htm</a></p>
