</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3504839787"  data-post-id='3504839787' data-root-id='3504839787' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='hNBVvLkN' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.90442000 14060420241046770601' data-json='{"post-id":"3504839787","root-id":"3504839787","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"hNBVvLkN","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.90442000 14060420241046770601","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223504839787\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223504839787\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022hNBVvLkN\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.90442000 14060420241046770601\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">High Fructose Corn Syrup vs Sugar Part I</div><p><strong><em>Let me preface this btw by saying that the actual answer to the question posed is in the next few HFCS vs Sugar posts.  I thought I&#8217;d give some background :p first.</em></strong></p>
<p><em>I came home after passing my ACLS/BLS certification to about 60 new tweets flying between @tymkrs, @v2kzay, and @talldarknweirdo with regards to high fructose corn syrup, sugar, and probably the state of man. </em></p>
<p>Anyway I&#8217;m going to attempt to give too long of an answer :) to the following tweet:</p>
<p>"Is there much difference between HFCS and a similar amount of straight sugar?  My understanding is they&#8217;re metabolized the same."</p>
<p><strong>Background:</strong></p>
<p>According to the USDA National Nutrient Database for Standard Reference,</p>
<p><strong>High Fructose Corn Syrup:</strong> There are two main types -</p>
<ol><li>HFCS 55: ~55% fructose and 42% glucose - mostly used in soft drinks</li>
<li>HFCS 42: ~42% fructose and 53% glucose - used in many foods and baked goods</li>
</ol><p>This was first created in 1957 but didn&#8217;t really start to grow until 1977.  A few reasons for this was new governmental production quotas of domestic sugar, subsidies of U.S. corn, and an import tariff on foreign sugar.  These combined to raise the price of sucrose to levels above those of the rest of the world and therefore made HFCS less costly for many sweetener applications.  So companies went to HFCS instead.</p>
<p>How is it made?  The simple answer:</p>
<ol><li>High-fructose corn syrup is produced by milling corn to produce corn starch.</li>
<li>Then processing that starch to yield corn syrup, which is almost entirely glucose</li>
<li>Then adding enzymes that change some of the glucose into fructose. The resulting syrup (after enzyme conversion) contains approximately 42% fructose and is HFCS 42. </li>
<li>The 42% fructose is then purified to 90% fructose, HFCS90. </li>
<li>To make HFCS 55, the HFCS 90 is mixed with HFCS 42 in the appropriate ratios to form the desired HFCS 55.</li>
</ol><p><strong>Table Sugar:</strong> Sucrose which is fructose and glucose linked weakly together.  When broken down during digestion it becomes 50% fructose, 50% glucose.</p>
<p>How is it made? Simply put:</p>
<ol><li>Mills extract raw sugar from freshly harvested cane</li>
<li>This raw sugar is mixed with heavy syrup and then centrifuged in a process called &#8216;affination&#8217; to wash away the sugar crystals&#8217; outer coating, which is less pure than the crystal interior. </li>
<li>The remaining sugar is then dissolved to make a syrup.</li>
<li>The syrup is &#8220;clarified&#8221; by adding a few chemicals which bind to impurities that can be taken away.</li>
<li>The clarified syrup is then decolorized, concentrated and repeatedly crystallized in a vacuum to produce white, refined sugar.</li>
</ol><p>Apparently due to tariffs, subsidies, and quotas, the price of table sugar in the US is nearly twice that of the rest of the world. <em>[looks through tables]</em></p>
<p>Holy Baloney.  I picked a random month/year to compare all of the prices:</p>
<ul><li>World Refined Sugar Prices Jan 2000: 7.70 cents/pound</li>
<li>US Refined Sugar Prices Jan 2000: 43.70 cents/pound</li>
<li>High Fructose Corn Syrup Prices Jan 2000: 15.78 cents/pound</li>
</ul><p>Let&#8217;s look at more recent prices shall we?</p>
<ul><li>World Refined Sugar Prices Jan 2011: 35.58 cents/pound</li>
<li>US Refined Sugar Prices Jan 2011: 65.20 cents/pound</li>
<li>High Fructose Corn Syrup Prices Jan 2011: 32.31 cents/pound</li>
</ul><p>Damn.  The HFCS people must have hella good lobbyists keeping real sugar at that price.</p>
<p>@atdiy/@tymkrs</p>
