            <div class="hover_tags"><span class="tags">                        #high fructose corn syrup #hfcs #sugar #fructose #glucose #sugar prices #hcfs vs sugar #tymkrs</span></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3485047165"  data-post-id='3485047165' data-root-id='3485047165' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='h7VB3FrM' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.92761000 1406042024684060923' data-json='{"post-id":"3485047165","root-id":"3485047165","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"h7VB3FrM","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.92761000 1406042024684060923","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223485047165\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223485047165\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022h7VB3FrM\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.92761000 1406042024684060923\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">Twelfth Ham lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>Resonance!  This however requires an understanding of the previous few posts on capacitors, inductors, and reactance.</p>
<p>Background:</p>
<p>Capacitors:</p>
<ul><li>Known as voltage smoothers</li>
</ul><p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgetozjlHx1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>The power source is constantly allowing the flow of current.  This current goes into all of the pathways possible - whether the light bulb or the capacitor.  So while the power source is driving this flow through the circuit, the capacitor is storing up current as potential energy (voltage in the form of farads - specifically the number of coulombs needed to change the capacitor&#8217;s energy potential by 1 volt).  If the power source drives at a lower voltage (maybe the battery&#8217;s weakening), you can think of it as a decrease in the pressure against the capacitor&#8217;s lid.  With this decrease, the capacitor will release some of its sequestered energy into the circuit.  The light bulb will be none the wiser because it&#8217;s still getting as much energy as it was before.  This is why capacitors are known as voltage smoothers - they make the light bulb think nothing&#8217;s changed with the power source.</p>
<ul><li>Changes in current are ahead of changes in voltage.</li>
</ul><p>A way I&#8217;ve come to understand this is&#8230;it is <em>because</em> of current going into the capacitor that it even develops a voltage (in the form of farads).  And likewise, it&#8217;s because of the current leaving the capacitor that voltage changes in not only the capacitor but also the circuit (as a circuit voltage smoother).  Therefore, you can say that current changes cause voltage changes in capacitors.  A before B.</p>
<p>Inductors:</p>
<ul><li>These are known as current smoothers - ie resist current changes.</li>
</ul><p>Inductors don&#8217;t like the current flow within them to change.  So whenever a circuit is broken, for instance, inductors induce a voltage within itself to force the current to remain flowing at the same amount it did before.</p>
<ul></ul><ul><li>Changes in voltage occur before changes in current.</li>
</ul><p>So unlike the capacitors where they use their current to prevent changes in voltage.  Inductors use a self-generated voltage to prevent changes in current.  And therefore if you look at it in the order that this happens - voltage will change before current changes.</p>
<ul></ul><p>Now. Because these two work opposite of each other (one going from current to voltage, and the other from voltage to current) - circuits that have both capacitors and inductors end up at a point where the two types of reactance are equal and cancel each other out.  These specific frequencies of AC current would therefore induce the condition called <strong>RESONANCE</strong>.  And the frequencies are known as <strong>resonant frequencies</strong>.</p>
<p>Circuits that have both capacitors and inductors will have at least one of these and are called <strong>resonant circuits</strong> or <strong>tuned circuits</strong>.  And in fact, radio users can use this property to their advantage because with variable capacitors or variable inductors, you can tune the circuit to either allow or prevent specific frequencies.</p>
<p>As the manual says: &#8220;A tuned circuit acts as a filter, passing or rejecting signals at its resonant frequency.  Tune circuits are important in radio because they help radios generate or receive signals at a single frequency.&#8221;</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve no exact idea how they actually do the filtering thing&#8230;but perhaps I&#8217;ll check into that.</p>
<p>@atdiy/@tymkrs</p></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
