</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3465775222"  data-post-id='3465775222' data-root-id='3465775222' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='rn7CJxTQ' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.94578800 14060420241355029257' data-json='{"post-id":"3465775222","root-id":"3465775222","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"rn7CJxTQ","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.94578800 14060420241355029257","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223465775222\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223465775222\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022rn7CJxTQ\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.94578800 14060420241355029257\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">Mics in the Tymkrs Studio - Part I</div><p>If you haven&#8217;t already, be sure to check the youtube we&#8217;ve got looking at the mics we&#8217;ve got in-house!  We show, disassemble (as much as we&#8217;re willing), and demonstrate differences in vocals between each of them.  If you wanted more information on the mics - here ya go!</p>
<p>Background:</p>
<p>Major Types of Microphones - Dynamic, Ribbon, Condenser (amongst others)</p>
<p><strong>Dynamic Microphones</strong> use an inductive coil connected to a diaphragm and  placed within the field of a permanent magnet. As the diaphragm moves,  it moves the coil, thus varying the voltage the coil produces. It seems that the majority of dynamic microphones have rugged coils which I think means that the coils won&#8217;t break if you drop it.  IE sturdier construction. And they usually have pretty high SPL (sound pressure level) capability.  *imagines a lumberjack singing&#8230;*</p>
<ul><li>Shure PG48 - Dynamic vocal microphone</li>
<li>Shure 55SH - Dynamic vocal microphone</li>
<li>Shure 520Dx - Has crystal diaphragm instead of coil</li>
</ul><p><strong>Ribbon Microphones</strong> are very delicate.  Instead of a diaphragm, however, they use a thin ribbon that  vibrates to vary voltage.  Ribbon mics are used in the studio for  recording voices and a broad range of instruments.  They soften the sound  and impart a warmth to recorded material.  They also have high SPL  capabilities and so can be placed very close to a sound source.</p>
<ul><li>Nady RSM-4: Short ribbon microphone</li>
<li>Cascade Victor: Long ribbon microphone</li>
</ul><p><strong>Condenser Microphones</strong> have a thin conductive diaphragm located close to a metal  plate called a backplate, creating a capacitor. The capacitor is  supplied with a small electric charge, either from phantom power or from  a battery. When the pressure of soundwaves cause the diaphragm to  vibrate, it changes the distance between it and the backplate, thus  causing variations in the output voltage. This varied output is the  microphone&#8217;s signal. </p>
<ul><li>MAudio Pulsar II Matched Stereo Pair: Small diaphragm condenser mics</li>
</ul><p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgzg52alle1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>The above illustrates different &#8220;polar patterns&#8221; or directions from which a mic will pick up the most sound. Cardioid means the mic is most sensitive from straight on and from the sides but  rejects sounds from 180 degrees opposite the direction the mic is aimed.  The supercardioid mic accepts a little more sound from a 180-degree  direction but rejects more from each side. The hypercardioid allows yet  more sound from 180 degrees but rejects more of the sound coming from 90  or 270 degrees.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ll go into the specific mics next..</p>
