</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3446374185"  data-post-id='3446374185' data-root-id='3446374185' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='xPmU3szX' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.95763200 1406042024637195522' data-json='{"post-id":"3446374185","root-id":"3446374185","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"xPmU3szX","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.95763200 1406042024637195522","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223446374185\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223446374185\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022xPmU3szX\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.95763200 1406042024637195522\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">11.875 Ham lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>Impedance(Z) = Combo of resistance and reactance.  It&#8217;s measured in ohms.</p>
<p>Background:</p>
<ul><li>Resistance - Prevents certain amounts of current from passing through the circuit.</li>
</ul><ul><li>Reactance - Resistance from capacitors and inductors to changes in AC current flow.  This leads to capacitors that resist changes in voltage and inductors that resist changes in current.  (Uh for more details please note my confusing posts earlier :p)</li>
</ul><p>Impedance is the TOTAL opposition to current flow in an AC circuit.  Simply put, impedance resists/impedes current flow.  So this term represents the total resistance a circuit has when either resistance, capacitive reactance, inductive reactance, or a combo of them is used.  Opposition to current flow in a DC circuit is simply known as resistance.</p>
<p>Another way of putting it is that impedance is a way of telling you how much of the voltage introduced at one end will make it to the other end.</p>
<p>In audio: <a href="http://forum.ecoustics.com/bbs/messages/34579/131527.html">http://forum.ecoustics.com/bbs/messages/34579/131527.html</a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.wisegeek.com/what-is-impedance.htm">http://www.wisegeek.com/what-is-impedance.htm</a></p>
<p><a href="http://artsites.ucsc.edu/EMS/music/tech_background/Z/impedance.html">http://artsites.ucsc.edu/EMS/music/tech_background/Z/impedance.html</a></p></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
