</div><div class="post post_micro is_photo post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3426088826"  data-post-id='3426088826' data-root-id='3426088826' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='OplsWwo2' data-type='photo' data-serve-id='0.96643500 1406042024131653813' data-json='{"post-id":"3426088826","root-id":"3426088826","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"OplsWwo2","type":"photo","serve-id":"0.96643500 1406042024131653813","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223426088826\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223426088826\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022OplsWwo2\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022photo\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.96643500 1406042024131653813\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_thumbnail_container has_imageurl" style="height: 101px; width: 150px;" data-imageurl="http://31.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgwodqQ8N41qffwoko1_r1_500.png"></div></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
     title=""><a target="_blank" class="hover"
               title=""
               href="http://tymkrs.tumblr.com/post/3426088826/ham-break-o-de-day-v0-01-id-like-to-take-a"><div class="hover_inner"><span class="post_date">Feb 21, 2011</span><span class="post_notes"
                        data-notes="3">3 notes</span></div>  

            <div class="hover_tags"><span class="tags">                        #series #parallel #current #voltage #AC #DC #resistors #capacitors #inductors #tymkrs #Ham Radio License Manual #Ham radio</span></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3404959692"  data-post-id='3404959692' data-root-id='3404959692' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='SIvqzaLH' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.99189700 1406042024996257612' data-json='{"post-id":"3404959692","root-id":"3404959692","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"SIvqzaLH","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.99189700 1406042024996257612","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223404959692\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223404959692\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022SIvqzaLH\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.99189700 1406042024996257612\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">11.75 Ham lesson o&#039; de day</div><p><strong>Reactance</strong> is [unwanted] resistance in a circuit element  (capacitor or inductor) to changes in current speed and/or direction.   Appropriately enough, <strong>capacitive reactance</strong> is created by capacitors, while <strong>inductive reactance</strong> is created by inductors.  It is most often associated with AC current  though when a DC current is first starting or stopping, a certain amount  of reactance may be experienced.</p>
<p>Background:</p>
<p><strong>Inductor:</strong> These are coils of wire and as current goes  through the wire, an electromagnetic force is created which helps to  keep current going at the same speeds.  When the circuit is broken, in  an effort to keep the current going at the same rate, inductors will use  the electromagnetic forces to pseudo create extra voltage to keep  electrons going.  This keeps up&#8230;until it can&#8217;t.</p>
<p><strong>Inductive Reactance Part 1</strong></p>
<p>From google searches, Inductive Reactance:</p>
<ol><li>Is the opposition of an inductor to changes in current caused by  build-up of magnetic fields.  These fields produce  counter-electromagnetic forces that oppose changes in the initial  current.</li>
<li> If current is increasing in magnitude, the induced voltage  will  “push against” the electron flow. <em>This makes sense - the more current, the more electric potential build up, and therefore the more induced voltage.  It&#8217;s like a spring.  The more you push on it, the harder it gets to push.  So to, the voltage will provide more resistance against subsequent electron flow.</em><strong><br /></strong></li>
<li>If current is decreasing, the   polarity will reverse and “push with” the electron flow to oppose the   decrease. <em>This makes sense if we know something about how inductors work - despite what was said in number 2, inductors want currents to stay at the same speed through them at all times, and if it starts to slow down, it&#8217;ll develop a voltage via electromagnetic forces to keep current up and so will &#8220;push with&#8221; the electron flow.</em></li>
<li>Inductors oppose <em>changes</em> in current through them, by dropping a voltage directly proportional to the <em>rate of change</em> of current.</li>
</ol><p><strong>Inductive Reactance Part 2</strong></p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lg8khca3Hf1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p><em>The  way I think about this is if you have a bar magnet as your inductor  with its N pole going up and it&#8217;s S pole going down.  And your current  is represented by another another bar magnet that has its pole S up N  down - to best attract to the inductor.  THEN AC current comes along and  flips your current so that both magnets have N pole up and S pole  down.  You&#8217;d end up with a bit of magnetic resistance until either the  inductor magnet flipped or the current flipped its polarity again (see  picture)</em></p>
<p>Per Wiki:</p>
<p>The back-emf is the source of the opposition to current flow.  A constant DC current has a zero rate-of-change, and sees an inductor as a short-circuit (it is typically made from a material with a low resistivity).  An alternating current  has a time-averaged rate-of-change that is proportional to frequency,  this causes the increase in inductive reactance with increased frequency.</p>
<p><strong>Inductive Reactance Part 3</strong></p>
<p>So you&#8217;ll remember that Capacitors are known as voltage smoothers.  Likewise, inductors are known as current smoothers (in a manner of speaking.  This is largely because their main action is preventing changes in current.  Let&#8217;s look at the phase difference in an inductor to see how this works:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfzc0wTWNZ1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<ol><li>Voltage dropped across an inductor is a reaction against the <em>change</em> in current through it.  <em>Ie inductors don&#8217;t want their current to change.</em></li>
<li>Voltage = zero  whenever current is at a peak (when current doesn&#8217;t increase or decrease).  <em>When current&#8217;s not changing, no voltage is induced to try to change that situation.</em></li>
<li>Voltage is at a  peak wherever the instantaneous current is at maximum change (the points  of steepest slope on the current wave, where it crosses the zero line - when current is traveling the fastest).  <em>When current is changing the most, the inductor is trying to get an induced voltage to work against that change.  </em></li>
<li>The voltage wave seems to  have a “head start” on the current wave; the voltage “leads” the  current, and the current “lags” behind the voltage.</li>
</ol><p>Again, I haven&#8217;t really reached my eureka moment, but I&#8217;ve been thinking about reactance for the past week and it hasn&#8217;t gotten better.  So if you&#8217;d like to help me out, feel free to leave a comment!!</p>
<p>@atdiy/@tymkrs</p>
<p><a href="http://www.allaboutcircuits.com/vol_2/chpt_3/2.html">http://www.allaboutcircuits.com/vol_2/chpt_3/2.html</a></p></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
