                        data-notes="22">22 notes</span></div>  

            <div class="hover_tags"><span class="tags">                        #inductor #inductive reactance #reactance #Ham Radio License Manual #Ham Radio #tymkrs</span></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3383866342"  data-post-id='3383866342' data-root-id='3383866342' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='9XpQWzCt' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.03198300 1406042025657136809' data-json='{"post-id":"3383866342","root-id":"3383866342","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"9XpQWzCt","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.03198300 1406042025657136809","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223383866342\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223383866342\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u00229XpQWzCt\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.03198300 1406042025657136809\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">11.5 Ham lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>So let&#8217;s actually get into what reactance and impedance are - shall we?!</p>
<p>[Cue a written and queued post.  Re-drafted. Deleted. Then three days of googling, then hemming and hawing about how to explain it in a way that anyone would understand it.]</p>
<p>So from all of my Google searches, there were a number of repeated definitions for reactance.</p>
<p><strong>Reactance</strong> is [unwanted] resistance in a circuit element (capacitor or inductor) to changes in current speed and/or direction.  Appropriately enough, <strong>capacitive reactance</strong> is created by capacitors, while <strong>inductive reactance</strong> is created by inductors.  It is most often associated with AC current though when a DC current is first starting or stopping from a newly closed/broken circuit, a certain amount of reactance may be experienced.</p>
<p>Background:</p>
<p><strong>Capacitor:</strong>  DC Current cannot pass through capacitors because capacitors are essentially parasitic breaks in the circuit.  Current ends up filling up the capacitor like a gas tank, and that&#8217;s it.  No more current can go through.  It can only come back out as released current.  AC current on the other hand, pushes and pulls.  It brings in current, then takes it back out with the tide.  That in and of itself creates a current.  In a circuit, you can tap between the power supply and the capacitor and there&#8217;ll still be current passing through. </p>
<p>Another way to think about it is that when a current is being forced into a capacitor, electric potential builds up inside of the capacitor - so to a certain extent, there is voltage inside that capacitor.  And when a capacitor is connected to a circuit, it always wants to &#8220;reequilibrate&#8221; or leak the power it&#8217;s been given back into the circuit and that allows them to be voltage smoothers (see capacitor lesson).</p>
<p>So from google, the search results consistently state the following.</p>
<p><strong>Capacitive Reactance Part 1</strong></p>
<ol><li>Deals with the changing electrical fields between two conductive surfaces.  </li>
</ol><ul><li>Initial thoughts: Duh. Capacitive reactance deals with capacitors which <em>is</em> &#8220;changing electrical fields between two conductive surfaces&#8221;. So what?</li>
<li>Is there internal resistance to the constant changing of where the electrons reside in the plate-dielectric-plate system of the capacitor?</li>
</ul><p>    2. Is resistance to changes in the initial voltage.</p>
<ul><li>Initial thoughts: Is there a constant voltage in the capacitor itself that current would have to fight against when moving back and forth?</li>
</ul><p><strong>Capacitive Reactance Part 2</strong></p>
<p>It&#8217;s been mentioned that an actual EXAMPLE of capacitors having reactance was the fact that they slowly leak out their electrical energy in a circuit as opposed to just releasing everything all at once.</p>
<ul><li>"In a circuit where the applied voltage signal is continually changing  from a positive cycle to a negative cycle at a rate that is determined by the frequency (a sine wave voltage), the  capacitor is either being charged or discharged on a continuous basis. <strong>As the capacitor charges or discharges a current  flows through it which itself is restricted by the internal resistance of the capacitor.</strong>" <a href="http://www.electronics-tutorials.ws/filter/filter_1.html">http://www.electronics-tutorials.ws/filter/filter_1.html</a></li>
<li><strong>A capacitor has a definitive time period for charging</strong> (T = RxC) The time T in seconds is equal to the resistance times the capacitance.  And it also takes the same amount of time to discharge.  And when AC is present across the terminals of a capacitor, it changes faster than the capacitor can charge and discharge.</li>
</ul><p><strong>Capacitive Reactance Part 3</strong></p>
<p>Strangely enough.  The faster the current goes back and forth from plate to plate (higher frequency), the less reactance (resistance) there seems to be.  Vice-versa, the slower the current goes back and forth from plate to plate (lower frequency), the more reactance (resistance) there seems to be.  <em>You&#8217;d think that the more back and forth there was, the more resistance that would be encountered.</em> </p>
<p>As the  frequency increases, the capacitor passes more charge across the plates in a given time resulting in a greater overall current flow  through the capacitor appearing as if the internal resistance of the capacitor has decreased.  Mind tricks! </p>
<p>Wiki has a nice explanation for this:</p>
<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_impedance">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_impedance</a></p>
<p>A DC voltage applied across a capacitor causes charge to accumulate on one side; the electric field due to the accumulated charge is the source of the opposition to the current. When the potential associated with the charge exactly balances the applied voltage, the current goes to zero.<em> So if you have 4.5 volts pushing a current into a capacitor, when the voltage in the capacitor = 4.5V, current stops.<br /></em></p>
<p>Driven by an AC supply, a capacitor will only accumulate a limited  amount of charge before the potential difference changes sign and the  charge dissipates. The higher the frequency, the less charge will  accumulate and the smaller the opposition to the current. </p>
<p><strong>Capacitive Reactance Part 4</strong></p>
<p>There is often talk of LAG and LEAD when explaining reactance.  This mainly having to do with the phase differences between current and voltage in a given resistive element:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfzc0k51PI1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<ol><li>Current = zero  whenever voltage is at a peak (Voltage is not changing but is at its highest/lowest measurable mark).  </li>
<li>Current is at a  peak wherever voltage is at maximum change (the points  of steepest slope on the voltage wave, where it crosses the zero line).  <em>And if you think about it - the faster that current is flowing into a capacitor, the more voltage that&#8217;s being sequestered in that capacitor.  Without current flow you don&#8217;t have an electric potential build up.</em></li>
<li>The current wave seems to  have a “head start” on the voltage wave: the current “leads” the  voltage, and the voltage “lags” behind the current.  </li>
<li>As a result: They say that current through a capacitor is a reaction against the <em>change</em> in voltage across it.  Ie when there&#8217;s a change in the voltage, the more change (whether the capacitor is getting more voltage or releasing voltage), the more current that passes through the capacitor.</li>
</ol><p>No idea!  I haven&#8217;t hit my eureka moment for capacitive reactance, but if you&#8217;d like to help explain it to me, I am /more than willing/ to hear you out!</p>
<p>@atdiy/@tymkrs</p>
