            <div class="hover_tags"><span class="tags">                        #Ham #Ham Radio #Ham Radio License Manual #capacitive reactance #capacitors #impedance #impedance #reactance #tymkrs #capacitive reactance #phase difference</span></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3364466418"  data-post-id='3364466418' data-root-id='3364466418' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='B4kA9E7H' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.06087800 14060420251677264503' data-json='{"post-id":"3364466418","root-id":"3364466418","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"B4kA9E7H","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.06087800 14060420251677264503","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223364466418\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223364466418\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022B4kA9E7H\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.06087800 14060420251677264503\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">11.25 Ham Lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>So I kinda took a whirlwind trip on that last post.  The next sentence is:</p>
<p>"In capacitors and inductors, the relationship between ac voltage and current is altered so that there&#8217;s an offset in time between changes in one and changes in the other as energy is stored, then released.  That means voltage and current have a <em>phase difference</em>.&#8221;</p>
<p>So I think this one came relatively easy to me simply because of how capacitors and inductors work.  We know they store energy.  I actually went through how they stored energy from a couple of posts ago.  And I mentioned that there is a delay in taking power away from an inductor and the <em>effects</em> of that power actually disappearing - as the magnetic field tries to keep current flow as fast as before.</p>
<p>I&#8217;d say it&#8217;s the same thing here.  There&#8217;s a delay between when you shut off the power and when you actually see the effect of that.  And a phase difference would just look like the following:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfzc0k51PI1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>This is the phase difference of a capacitor.  In a capacitor, as voltage increases, the capacitor charges up (filling up a gas tank). Thus a large initial current/influx of electrons.  As the voltage peaks, the  capacitor gets full up and the current falls to zero since no more electrons can flow in that direction.  This circuit reverses and the charge leaves the capacitor.</p>
<ul><li><strong>Point A:</strong> The voltage is zero and the  capacitor is uncharged. Initially, the voltage increases quickly. The  voltage across the capacitor matches the power supply voltage, so the  current is large enough to build up charge on the capacitor plates. The closer  the voltage gets to its peak, the slower it changes, meaning less  current has to flow. </li>
<li>When the voltage reaches a peak at <strong>Point B</strong>, the  capacitor is fully charged and the current is momentarily zero.  After this peak, the voltage starts dropping - <em>I suppose this is because the need for the voltage has disappeared.</em>  </li>
<li>For the capacitor to discharge/release its stored energy, the current has to reverse its direction. When  the voltage passes through zero at <strong>Point C</strong>, it&#8217;s changing quite rapidly;  to match this voltage the current must be large and negative.  <em>I wonder if this has anything to do with the polarity of ac current going from positive to negative polarity?</em></li>
<li>Step 3 - Between <strong>Points C and D</strong>, the voltage is negative. Charge  builds up again on the capacitor plates, but the polarity is opposite to  what it was in step one.  With the negative voltage, the current is also negative, and as the  voltage reaches its negative peak at <strong>Point D</strong> the current drops to zero.</li>
<li>Step 4 - After <strong>Point D</strong>, the voltage heads toward zero and the  capacitor must discharge.  When the voltage reaches zero it&#8217;s gone  through a full cycle so it&#8217;s back to <strong>Point A</strong> again to repeat the cycle.  Again, like a pendulum.</li>
</ul><p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfzc0wTWNZ1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>This is the phase difference of an inductor.  In inductors, however the voltage changes, the current tries to oppose that  change.  <em>Remember it&#8217;s like the car trying to rev up to get to highway speeds.  Imagine having to do that then slow down to 30mph, then rev up again.  You end up with dealing with the resistance of the car. </em> When the voltage is not changing there is no current and no  magnetic field.</p>
<ul><li>As the voltage from the power source increases from zero, the voltage  on the inductor matches it. <em>With the capacitor, the voltage came from  the charge stored on the capacitor plates (or, equivalently, from the  electric field between the plates). </em>With the inductor, the voltage comes  from changing the flux/current through the coil, which changes the magnetic field in the coil.</li>
<li>To produce a large positive voltage, a large increase in current  is required. When the voltage passes through zero, the current should  stop changing just for an instant. When the voltage is large and  negative, the current should be decreasing quickly.</li>
</ul><p>Thanks to:</p>
<p><a href="http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Electronics/AC_Voltage_and_Current">http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Electronics/AC_Voltage_and_Current</a></p>
<p><a href="http://physics.bu.edu/~duffy/py106/ACcircuits.html">http://physics.bu.edu/~duffy/py106/ACcircuits.html</a></p>
