            <div class="hover_tags"><span class="tags">                        #Ham Radio License Manual #Ham Radio #reactance #impedance #direct current #resistors in series circuits #resistors in parallel circuits #alternating currents #in phase #tymkrs</span></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3328419303"  data-post-id='3328419303' data-root-id='3328419303' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='3jdEwGQV' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.11333800 14060420251410946696' data-json='{"post-id":"3328419303","root-id":"3328419303","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"3jdEwGQV","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.11333800 14060420251410946696","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223328419303\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223328419303\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u00223jdEwGQV\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.11333800 14060420251410946696\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">10.75 Ham Lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>Whoever said electronics are boring clearly never got to play with the totally ADJUSTABLE and VARIABLE capacitors, resistors, and inductors!  Forget the old static components, you can actually CHANGE how they let flow through!</p>
<p>[Insert excited.gif here]</p>
<p><strong>Resistors:</strong> Gatekeepers for current.  They prevent specific amounts of current from getting through.</p>
<ul><li><strong>Variable resistor:</strong> Allows you to control how much resistance a circuit has to deal with in a given spot.  The way it works is there are three terminals.  Let&#8217;s label them 1, 2, and 3.  </li>
</ul><p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfx3esOLxO1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>Because Terminal 2 is connected to the output, it can receive signals ranging from Ground (no signal) to Input (maximal signal).</p>
<ol><li>Terminal 1 - Usually connected to ground</li>
<li>Terminal 2 - Wiper - Connected to output</li>
<li>Terminal 3 - Connected to input</li>
</ol><ul><li>The terminal in the middle is the WIPER, and the other two are known as ENDs.  The wiper travels along a circular resistive strip when the knob is turned.  Resistance is measured with respect to the wiper and either one of the end terminals. </li>
<li>The closer  the wiper is to the end terminal it is wired in conjunction with (let&#8217;s assume terminal 3), the  less the resistance, because the path of the current will be shorter.  The further away it moves from the terminal, the greater the resistance  will be.  </li>
<li>Said in another way.  If there is ZERO resistance at End Terminal 3, when you make the wiper go counter-clockwise, the current has to travel farther along the resistive element in the squiggly lines to leave the circuit, which takes a longer amount of time, and requires the current to get past more resistance.  So when you finally reach Terminal 1 (associated w/ground) - you end up with hardly any signal.</li>
</ul><p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfx2yhQ2pa1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<ul><li>Example: Volume Control, Light Dimmer</li>
</ul><p><strong>Capacitors:</strong> Store certain amounts of current that can be released over time or just sequestered (until abruptly released).  Remember they consist of electrodes with dielectric material between them.</p>
<ul><li><strong>Variable capacitor: </strong>These allow for changing the amount of capacitance a capacitor stores.  The rotor-stator type of variable capacitor shown below shows how you can rotate a set of plates to overlap less or more with another set of plates.  The more overlap there is, the more capacitance there is, and therefore the greater the ability to store electricity. </li>
<li>Example: Radio Tuner</li>
</ul><p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfx4p7LtDu1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p><strong> Inductors:</strong> Stores magnetic energy caused by a current going through a wire.</p>
<ul><li><strong>Variable Inductors:</strong> These can be made by changing the number of coils that an inductor has, or even how far a magnetic bar reaches inside the coils.   Moving the core farther inside = higher inductance.  And decreasing the number of coils an inductor has = lower inductance.</li>
<li>Example: Radio Tuning as well</li>
</ul><p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfx58coibI1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p><strong>Transformers:</strong> Made from two/more inductors that share their stored energy.  This allows energy to be transferred from one inductor to another. </p>
<ul><li>Example: transferring energy from a 120V AC outlet to a lower voltage for electronic equipment.</li>
</ul><p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfx5deVtF11qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p><a href="http://www.brighthub.com/engineering/electrical/articles/47625.aspx">http://www.brighthub.com/engineering/electrical/articles/47625.aspx</a></p>
