                        data-notes="9">9 notes</span></div>  

            <div class="hover_tags"><span class="tags">                        #Resistors #variable resistors #capacitors #variable capacitors #rotor-stator #transformers #Ham Radio License Manual #Ham Radio</span></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3310795034"  data-post-id='3310795034' data-root-id='3310795034' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='6kjWKXCU' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.14690900 14060420251376100221' data-json='{"post-id":"3310795034","root-id":"3310795034","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"6kjWKXCU","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.14690900 14060420251376100221","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223310795034\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223310795034\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u00226kjWKXCU\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.14690900 14060420251376100221\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">10.5 Ham lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>Inductors!  &#8220;These store magnetic energy in the magnetic field created by current flowing through a wire.  This is called inductance and is measured in henrys (H).&#8221;</p>
<p><strong>Inductors Part 1</strong></p>
<p><em>This statement makes a few assumptions about what we know:</em></p>
<p><em>1) That we knew that magnetic fields could be created by current going through a wire.</em></p>
<p><em>2) That we knew that magnetic energy could be stored.</em></p>
<p><em>3) That inductance sounds like something I would understand.</em></p>
<p>It seems that this would require us to look at ELECTROMAGNETS.  Essentially, when <em>any</em> charged particle moves, it creates a magnetic &#8220;tunnel/field&#8221; around its path  of travel, and that magnetic field moves with the  particle, constantly surrounding it.  The area of influence depends on the strength of the  magnetic field, which is directly related to the cross-sectional area of  the conductor (wire vs bar), the rate of flow of the current and the change in  direction of its flow (AC vs DC). </p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfwxj6ICTw1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>The green is the cross section of a given wire, and the rings around it represent the magnetic field as current passes through it.  The closer the rings are, the stronger the magnetism.</p>
<p>The main way they found out about this, I imagine, is by experimentation.</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfwxku3Ete1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>So if you hook a battery up to a wire that is coiled around a nail, you&#8217;d figure out that you&#8217;d be able to pick up paper clips and other items that had magnetic properties.  And indeed, the strong the magnetic properties of whatever you wrap the coil around, the stronger the magnet.</p>
<p>And from just that example, coils were found to be more efficient magnets than just plain wires with current running through them.  The coils and each of their respective electromagnetic fields ADD up as they get closer to each other.  So from just a few coils, what was a super weak magnetic field as a straight wire, now is something that can do something.</p>
<p><strong>Inductors Part 2</strong></p>
<p>That&#8217;s essentially what an <strong>inductor</strong> is - a coiled piece of wire.  When current runs through it, it develops a magnetic field.  Now the question becomes, how is this magnetic energy stored? </p>
<p>So, the way I understood this was that when the current first starts going through the wire of the inductor, there&#8217;s a certain amount of resistance - kind of like when you&#8217;re on a ramp merging onto the highway, and how you have to speed up to get to that 60-70mph.  There&#8217;s that bit of time that you haven&#8217;t gotten the magnetic field set up yet.  But then once you&#8217;re at 60 mph, it&#8217;s easier to stay that way.  Current is like that in an inductor.  There&#8217;s a little bit of resistance which may require more power, but once the current and magnetic field is established, the current will prefer staying at that speed.</p>
<ul><li>The analogy of inductance in the physical world is the inertia of the   mass of an object.  It requires a force to get it moving, but once it&#8217;s   moving it tends to keep moving.  That&#8217;s similar to the way current acts   in an inductor.  The higher the inductance (mass) the slower the  current  increases (velocity) for a given voltage (force).  <a href="http://www.electro-tech-online.com/general-electronics-chat/43023-choke-coils.html">http://www.electro-tech-online.com/general-electronics-chat/43023-choke-coils.html</a></li>
</ul><p>Say the power source is turned off or the circuit is broken.  The magnetic field in the wire doesn&#8217;t just like to stop the current it&#8217;s helping through.  It wants to maintain that same current speed that it had been enjoying before - so it squeezes the last bit of juice (increasing what voltage it has) that it can before giving up.  In other words, in the way that the capacitor current spikes when you short it, the inductor voltage spikes when you open the circuit. </p>
<p><em>Note: As a capacitor stores and releases energy in a circuit, it smooths out voltage changes.  But as inductors store and release energy, they smooth out current changes.</em></p>
<p>An inductor&#8217;s ability to store magnetic energy is measured by its inductance in units of henries (H).  Therefore, inductance is essentially the property of a circuit storing energy in the form of an electromagnetic field.  It&#8217;s also the property of opposing changes in current (as explained above). </p>
<ul><li>An important thing to note is that inductors will easily allow direct current to go through, but not alternating current.  Remember, inductors oppose changes in current, and that&#8217;s all that AC is, a back and forth change in current direction.  So sometimes inductors are called &#8220;chokes&#8221; and are used to block ac signals.</li>
</ul><p><strong>Inductors Part 3: Quasi Summary</strong></p>
<ul><li>Inductors react against changes in current by dropping voltage in the polarity necessary to oppose the change. </li>
<li>When an inductor is faced with an increasing current, it acts as a load: dropping voltage as it absorbs energy (negative on the current entry side and positive on the current exit side, like a resistor).</li>
<li>When an inductor is faced with a decreasing current, it acts as a power source: creating voltage as it releases stored energy (positive on the current entry side and negative on the current exit side, like a battery).</li>
</ul><p>To actually measure this&#8230;.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.coilgun.info/theoryinductors/measureinductance.htm">http://www.coilgun.info/theoryinductors/measureinductance.htm</a></p>
<p>(or google how to measure inductance) - cuz &#8230;.there&#8217;s no easy way!</p>
<p>Sources for certain pics/explanations:</p>
<p><a href="http://wiki.answers.com/Q/How_do_electromagnets_work">http://wiki.answers.com/Q/How_do_electromagnets_work</a></p>
<p><a href="http://answers.yahoo.com/question/index?qid=20090710105759AAmNVy6">http://answers.yahoo.com/question/index?qid=20090710105759AAmNVy6</a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.allaboutcircuits.com/vol_1/chpt_15/1.html">http://www.allaboutcircuits.com/vol_1/chpt_15/1.html</a></p>
