</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3293353839"  data-post-id='3293353839' data-root-id='3293353839' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='uRG7Owuc' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.17111300 1406042025898372511' data-json='{"post-id":"3293353839","root-id":"3293353839","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"uRG7Owuc","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.17111300 1406042025898372511","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223293353839\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223293353839\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022uRG7Owuc\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.17111300 1406042025898372511\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">10.375 Ham lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>How to read Capacitors!</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfvbp313Ag1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>Here is a picture of what I&#8217;d think would be a typical capacitor  that people see on their circuit boards/bread boards, whatever. To read  the capacitor&#8217;s side:</p>
<p>This means the capacitor has 2200 micro-farads of storage capacity,  with an upper voltage rating of 16 volts alternating current.</p>
<p>1) <strong>Nominal Capacitance:</strong> 2200 microfarads - The value  of the capacitance, C of a  capacitor, is measured in pico-Farads (pF),  nano-Farads (nF) or micro-Farads (µF) and is marked onto the body of  the capacitor as numbers, letters or coloured bands.</p>
<p>2) <strong>Working Voltage:</strong> 16v - The working voltage is the  maximum continuous voltage (either DC or AC) that can be  applied to  the capacitor without failure during its working life.</p>
<p>3) <strong>Polarization:</strong> The majority of  capacitors have  their negative terminal clearly marked with either a black stripe, band,  arrows or chevrons down one side of their body as shown, to prevent any  incorrect connection to the DC  supply.</p>
<ul><li>With both leads of the capacitor coming out of the same end,  that black band is on the side of the negative lead.  And if you have a  capacitor where the leads come out on opposite ends, the arrow will  point to let you know which way the negative lead is.</li>
</ul><p>4) <strong>Tolerance (±%):</strong> Sometimes, capacitors also have a tolerance rating and reflects the range of potential capacitance that that particular capacitor can hold.  So a 100µF capacitor with a ±20% tolerance could legitimately vary from 80µF to 120µF and still remain within tolerance.  The most common tolerance variation for capacitors is 5% or 10% but some plastic capacitors are rated as low as ±1%.</p>
<p>5) <strong>Working Temperature (T):</strong> Changes in temperature can affect the capacitance because of any changes in the dielectric medium.  The normal working range for most  capacitors is -30°C to +125°C with nominal voltage ratings.  These are often written on the actual capacitor as well.</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfvecaihoI1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>These are examples that include all of the specifications I detailed earlier.  And for more details on other characteristics that capacitors have:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.electronics-tutorials.ws/capacitor/cap_3.html">http://www.electronics-tutorials.ws/capacitor/cap_3.html</a></p>
<p>Sometimes, if the capacitor is too small, it&#8217;ll use a &#8220;code&#8221; much like how resistors use color bands to be deciphered.  Here&#8217;s an example:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfvei3mUS21qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>Let&#8217;s take the 203M capacitor and see what its capacitance is.</p>
<p>So like in resistors: the 2 = 1<sup>st</sup> digit, the 0 = 2<sup>nd</sup> digit, the 3 is the multiplier in  pico-Farads, pF and the letter M is the tolerance  	and this translates to:	<br /><br />   20pF * 1,000 (3 zero&#8217;s) = 20,000&#160;pF , 20nF or 0.020 uF</p>
<p>The M indicates a tolerance of +/- 20%</p>
<p>The following link is a good place to look further into deciphering how much capacitance a capacitor has depending on color bands and letters/numbers.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.electronics-tutorials.ws/capacitor/cap_5.html">http://www.electronics-tutorials.ws/capacitor/cap_5.html</a></p>
