</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3217915967"  data-post-id='3217915967' data-root-id='3217915967' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='t9Y2Kwu1' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.29840700 1406042025173137532' data-json='{"post-id":"3217915967","root-id":"3217915967","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"t9Y2Kwu1","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.29840700 1406042025173137532","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223217915967\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223217915967\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022t9Y2Kwu1\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.29840700 1406042025173137532\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">BitCoin Digital Currency</div><p>We were watching Security Now w/@sggrc Steve Gibson on TwiT of Gibson Research Corporation and he introduced a rather intriguing and hopefully world-changing digital currency.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s called BitCoin and is a decentralized, peer-to-peer digital currency.  There is no central authority to issue new money or keep track of transactions (ie no Federal Reserve!).   This helps because the value of the bitcoin won&#8217;t go down because some central authority decides to print a few million bucks more.  You can exchange USD for bitcoin, and wherever <strong>bitcoin is accepted</strong>, you can use it to purchase whatever stuff/service you need. </p>
<p>Transactions are always free, unlike other online payment systems that may take anywhere from 1-5% per transaction + other fees.  Payment can be sent without middlemen or other third parties.  So you never have to worry about &#8220;big brother&#8221; keeping track of what you&#8217;re buying or selling.  OR preventing/controlling those transactions.</p>
<p>Payments are irreversible.  So if you send it, you&#8217;ve sent it.  If you&#8217;ve gotten bitcoin from a customer, you&#8217;ve gotten it.  And if you need a refund, the recipient can send it voluntarily as just another Send transaction.  These transactions can also be as anonymous as you want it to be.  &#8220;Transactions are only identified by your Bitcoin address and you can have as many as you want.&#8221;</p>
<p>Security-wise, @whixr says I wouldn&#8217;t be able to understand it :).  So I&#8217;ll direct you to a few other sites that I believe have better ideas about the amount of security.  But from what I&#8217;ve read, it&#8217;s supposed to be even more secure than current online banking encryption.</p>
<p>Might be neat to check this out.   Here are some links to get you started:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.bitcoin.org/">http://www.bitcoin.org/</a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.bitcoinme.com/">http://www.bitcoinme.com/</a></p>
<p><a href="http://freebitcoins.appspot.com/">http://freebitcoins.appspot.com/</a></p>
<p>@atdiy/@tymkrs</p>
<p>And if you want to donate some Bitcoins to Toymaker Television (we&#8217;ll use them to help produce more content) our Bitcoin address is:</p>
