</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source no_notes has_hover" id="post_micro_3200230216"  data-post-id='3200230216' data-root-id='3200230216' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='zTdPlltw' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.32832800 1406042025593591783' data-json='{"post-id":"3200230216","root-id":"3200230216","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"zTdPlltw","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.32832800 1406042025593591783","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223200230216\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223200230216\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022zTdPlltw\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.32832800 1406042025593591783\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">Ponderings re:Comment II</div><p><em>Again - thanks to Mark @brainwagon for taking the time to correct my noobish tendencies!  I often forget that the words that I use may have a specific meaning when dealing with circuits, and my usage of &#8220;power&#8221; is a clear example of that!  I&#8217;ll go through this comment and hopefully be able to edit my original post on resistance.</em></p>
<p>I really like this series, mostly because I am self taught in this  arena, and I find that trying to explain stuff (as you are doing)  clarifies certain things, and makes you realize that you really don&#8217;t  know what you think you know.</p>
<p><em>Self taught FTW!  Fortunately I know that I don&#8217;t know anything :) It&#8217;s convincing myself that I&#8217;m still able to learn new things in fields I wouldn&#8217;t have caught myself dead trying to figure out two years ago!</em><br /><br />I think there are a couple of  misleading things above.   While it is called &#8220;Ohm&#8217;s law&#8221;, it isn&#8217;t  really a law.  Ohm&#8217;s law is the linear, constant relationship between  voltage and current, but many materials don&#8217;t exhibit such a constant  relationship.   For instance, a light bulb&#8217;s resistance actually varies  significantly with changes in voltage, because heating will actually  cause the resistance of  the filament to increase.  <br /><br /><a href="http://wiki.answers.com/Q/Circuits_that_Do_not_obey_ohm%27s_law">http://wiki.answers.com/Q/Circ&#8230;</a></p>
<p><em>I think when I was first trying to explain it, I was trying to just provide the basics without accounting for all of the contingencies.  I&#8217;m trying to &#8220;build up&#8221; as I go.  So when I learn something later that gives me a eureka moment, I make sure to address it, and come back to edit previous posts.  On resistance: I believe I have a post on resistors coming up shortly that&#8217;ll address the basics of temperature affecting resistors.</em></p>
<p>And  of course things like diodes or transistors don&#8217;t display linear  relationships between voltage and charge either, so we should be  careful.</p>
<p><em>Heh I&#8217;ll be getting to that!</em><br /><br />I also think that you are a teensy bit careless with  words that describe &#8220;speed&#8221;.  <strong>For instance, when you say that the &#8220;lower  the resistance, the faster the current can go through the material&#8221;,  it&#8217;s actually the rate that the charge can be moved through the resistor  that increases</strong>.   <strong>Current and charge aren&#8217;t the same thing: one ampere  of current for one second moves 1 coulomb of charge (6.24E18 electrons).   Lower resistance means that more electrons per second can move through  the resistor.   Lower resistance means more current can move through  the resistor. </strong></p>
<p><em>You are right, this is an important distinction to make.  I might want to warn the readers, I may get this wrong, because to make it easier on myself I&#8217;ve equated the two, but Current is almost the amount of electrons whereas speed has to do with the actual electrons/charge themselves.  (If I&#8217;m not mistaken).  I&#8217;ll put this note in the original post and edit accordingly! </em><br /><br />You are getting a bit ahead of yourself when you  talk about &#8220;power&#8221; too.   Since P = I E and E = I R, then P = I^2 R (or P  = E^2 / R).   When you say &#8220;the higher the resistance, the more voltage  you need to push through current&#8221;, it&#8217;s important to remember what you  are holding constant and what you are varying.</p>
<p><em>Oh hah, I wasn&#8217;t even thinking about power power, I was thinking of juice/oomph/probably voltage.  And in looking at your next example/drawing it out/etc - I think I was keeping current constant.  So to keep current going at the same rate&#8230;with a higher resistance, you&#8217;d require more voltage. And the less resistance, the less voltage.  Does that work?<br /></em></p>
<p>Let&#8217;s imagine a battery  and resistor hooked into a circuit, with the battery voltage being 1v  and the resistance being 100 ohms.   We can solve for the current (I = E  / R, or 0.01 amps).   If we increase the resistance to (say) 1000 ohms,  the current goes down to 0.001 amps).   The power dissipated by the two  circuits are just the voltage times current or 0.01 watts and 0.001  watts respectively.  <strong>Hence, increasing resistance actually _decreases_  the power and the current in the circuit. </strong></p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lgcgblm4rE1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p><em>To be redundant: Voltage is being kept constant in this example.  When the resistance increased from 100 to 1000ohms, the amount of current going through decreased from 0.01 to 0.001 amps.  Increased resistance = decreased current.  When we look at how much power is going through the resistor with these specifications, the more resistance, the less power.</em></p>
<p>The situation which  you describe is to try to maintain the same current while increasing the  resistance.  In that case, you have to increase the voltage by the same  proportion.  </p>
<p><em>Sweet, I figured out what I was keeping constant before coming to this statement.  So yes, I was trying to keep the same current while increasing the resistance.  And that&#8217;s probably why I said that the higher the resistance, the higher the amount of voltage needed to push the current through.</em><br /><br />Is this being too pedantic?   I&#8217;ll stop if this isn&#8217;t helpful.</p>
<p><em>Nope, this was a great way for me to actually stop and smell the numbers.  I&#8217;ve been trying to avoid them and just take things from a theoretical point of view, but it seems that when I actually dive into the numbers, I discover eureka moments :p.  So if you would like to keep commenting/correcting me - I&#8217;ll keep using them as learning experiences!!  SUPER mucho thanks :)</em></p>
<p><br /><em>@atdiy/@tymkrs</em></p></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
