            <div class="hover_tags"><span class="tags">                        #diy learning #ohm's law #resistors and temperature #current vs charge #Power #voltage #resistance and current #resistance and power #brainwagon #tymkrs</span></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source no_notes has_hover" id="post_micro_3182627685"  data-post-id='3182627685' data-root-id='3182627685' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='vHzF20vK' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.35150000 14060420251426071367' data-json='{"post-id":"3182627685","root-id":"3182627685","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"vHzF20vK","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.35150000 14060420251426071367","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223182627685\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223182627685\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022vHzF20vK\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.35150000 14060420251426071367\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">Ninth Ham lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>Power!! It&#8217;s power (P)!!!</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfq3usLVx61qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>Power is measured in watts which are abbreviated as W. </p>
<p>1) Power is the rate at which electrical energy is used.</p>
<p>2) Power is the product of voltage and current. (P = E x I)</p>
<p>3) The amount of power consumed is the <strong>load </strong>applied to a circuit.</p>
<ul><li>With Ohm&#8217;s Law (E = I x R)&#8230;you can substitute E and I with their relative equivalents</li>
</ul><p>P = E x I</p>
<p>P = <em>(I x R)</em> x I = <strong>P = I</strong><sup>2</sup><strong> x R           (Substituted E with I x R)<br /></strong></p>
<p>P = E x <em>(E / R)</em> = <strong>P = E</strong><sup>2</sup><strong> / R         (Substituted I with E / R)</strong></p>
<p>With those equations you can find out  how much power is being used in a circuit, or how many amps are flowing when voltage is x and load is y.</p>
<p>Blah blah.</p>
<p>AC/DC! </p>
<p>This is a bit of a more interesting topic.  It talks about the direction of current flow.  If the electrons flow in ONE direction, that&#8217;s DIRECT CURRENT - DC.  And current that regularly reverses direction is ALTERNATING CURRENT - AC.</p>
<p>So if you look at a voltmeter and check to see what the voltage is in a given circuit, and you see that it&#8217;s a constant +1.5v or 1.5v, you&#8217;ll know that it&#8217;s a DC voltage flowing through.  If however you see the voltage swinging between +1.5 and -1.5 within a short time, you&#8217;ll know that you&#8217;re dealing with an AC voltage.  In other words, DC voltage has the same polarity all of the time and AC voltage has regularly reversing polarity.</p>
<p>When off:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfv2xth2Jf1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>The circuit is broken so the electrons don&#8217;t have a path to travel on.</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfv2zvqSSd1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>With the AC generator now linked - you see the electrons shifting back and forth - but still powering the light bulb.  Household power is AC power in the 50-60Hz range.</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfv30tF1Bp1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>And batteries are DC voltage and you can see that the electrons move in only one direction - and light up the light bulb.</p>
<p>One cycle of AC involves:  AC flowing &#8212;&gt; stopping &#8212;&gt; reversing &#8212;&gt; and stopping again. (Think of a pendulum)</p>
<p>One cycle of AC <em>voltage</em> involves: Zero &#8212;&gt; AC voltage building up &#8212;&gt; Reversal to negative polarity &#8212;&gt; Return to zero.  This is a sine wave pattern, just like a radio signal.</p>
<p>@atdiy/@tymkrs</p>
<p>(GIFs courtesy of <a href="http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/edison/sfeature/acdc.html">http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/edison/sfeature/acdc.html</a>)</p></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
     title=""><a target="_blank" class="hover"
