                        data-notes="12">12 notes</span></div>  

            <div class="hover_tags"><span class="tags">                        #Ohm's Law made easy #resistance #ohmmeter #insulator #Ham Radio License Manual #ham radio #relationship between resistance and voltage #Ohm's Law #tymkrs</span></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3146037470"  data-post-id='3146037470' data-root-id='3146037470' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='DnryurOQ' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.41754400 14060420251011323560' data-json='{"post-id":"3146037470","root-id":"3146037470","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"DnryurOQ","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.41754400 14060420251011323560","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223146037470\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223146037470\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022DnryurOQ\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.41754400 14060420251011323560\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">7.5 Ham Lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>So now that we&#8217;ve <em>kinda</em> figured out the difference between serial and parallel with regards to current and voltage:</p>
<p><strong>Serial</strong> &#8212;&gt; <em>Constant</em> current over the whole circuit but <em>varying </em>voltages depending on the elements ability to prevent the current from moving forward (ie resistance).</p>
<p><strong>Parallel </strong>&#8212;&gt; <em>Varying</em> current based on number of elements and their energy requirements.  You will find that there is constant voltage across similar elements (even if you keep adding to the number of elements present) as long as you don&#8217;t overwhelm the current capacity.</p>
<p><em>As far as I understand anyway</em>.</p>
<p>This helps to understand how the meters work for measuring voltage and amperage. </p>
<p><strong>Ammeter: </strong>To find current, you want to connect your  meter in series fashion.  That way the current flows through it - as  water through a dam - and you&#8217;re but that gate that&#8217;s measuring the  flow.  And it&#8217;ll need to be a very low-resistance meter to get the most  accurate reading as series circuits are affected by resistance-having  elements.</p>
<p><strong>Voltmeter: </strong>To find the voltage, you want to be able to link your meter in a <em>parallel</em> fashion because once your meter is in parallel fashion, it becomes just another element and you can see what kind of voltage amounts are being given to the other elements as well.</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfk2ir6MFD1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p><em>Ammeter on the left - Voltmeter on the right: This shows how they work being in series and parallel respectively.</em></p>
<p><strong>Multimeter: </strong>This rolls everything into one, including an Ohmmeter, which I&#8217;ll go into later.  This is an all-in-one exclusive package for 12.99 from your local hardware store and measures voltage, current, and resistance. <em>(Btw, no idea why they get so expensive so fast on Parts Express)</em><strong><br /></strong></p>
<p><em>The example the manual gives is that if you&#8217;re measuring the resistance of a circuit and the reading starts out low but gradually increases, that could be a large value capacitor.</em></p>
<p>And it is possible to break a multimeter - which I didn&#8217;t know - if you&#8217;re trying to measure voltage or connecting the lines to an energized circuit when trying to measure resistance, that could damage a multimeter.  <em>I.e. watch what the meter&#8217;s on before sticking the red and black wires on a circuit!</em></p>
<p>Pictures!</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfk2ueqiXS1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>(From Doctronics.co.uk - excellent pics of these)</p>
<p>The above is a multimeter.  I&#8217;ll write a post on how to use a multimeter once I learn about AC/DC and resistance :p&#8230;</p>
