            <div class="hover_tags"><span class="tags">                        #audio foam #bass trap #circuit breaker #construction #demo #demolition #diy #do it yourself #ducts #home recording studio #homebrew #how to #isolation booth #live room #netcast #new media #podcast #remodeling #sound proofing #sound stage #streaming #vocal booth #wiers</span></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source no_notes has_hover" id="post_micro_3125276033"  data-post-id='3125276033' data-root-id='3125276033' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='T42qQxRp' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.45790100 1406042025497858245' data-json='{"post-id":"3125276033","root-id":"3125276033","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"T42qQxRp","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.45790100 1406042025497858245","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223125276033\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223125276033\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022T42qQxRp\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.45790100 1406042025497858245\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">Ponderings re:Comment</div><p>Thanks for the added help Mark - I&#8217;m posting your comment to go through each bit and then comment on what I understood and what I didn&#8217;t understand.</p>
<p>The behavior of all these circuits can be understood a bit more formally by considering Ohms law (E = I R) and Kirchoff&#8217;s circuit laws.    These state that the sum of all currents into and out of any node in the  circuit must sum to zero (this is just conservation of charge) and that  the sum of the (signed) voltage drops must sum to zero for each loop  through the circuit.</p>
<p><em>By &#8220;all currents/voltage into and out of&#8221; you must mean the current/voltage going into a given node has a positive value to it and that same current/voltage coming out of the node has a negative value to it.   Since the current going into the circuit is essentially the same as the current coming out..<strike>.[thought processes kicking in]  Now. Does this actually work for resistors?</strike></em><strike><em>  Especially since resistors slow current down&#8230;so the current going in doesn&#8217;t equal the current going out and therefore the sum can&#8217;t be zero?</em>  </strike><em>The aforementioned were my initial thoughts until I finally realized that I wasn&#8217;t even calculating current correctly.  Either way, now that I&#8217;ve gotten it, yes this makes sense :)</em><br /><br />If you have a battery voltage feeding a pair  of light bulbs (which are really just resistors that emit light) in  parallel, the voltage drop around each of the two circuits must be the  same, and equal to the battery in magnitude.   However, the current is  split between the two, since the total current leaving the battery is  split into the two currents (which are equal when the bulbs present  equal resistance) so the current must be half the current supplied by  the battery.</p>
<p><em>This made sense. I think the way I explained it was that current increases up until the voltage can&#8217;t handle it? I don&#8217;t know if that&#8217;s accurate though.</em><br /><br />The case with two bulbs in series is similar.  The  total drop in voltage must be 1/2 the battery voltage (the circuit can  be thought of as a voltage divider).    The current around the circuit  is limited to the total series resistance (sum of the two bulb&#8217;s  resistance) and the voltage (I = E / R), but the entire current goes to  both bulbs.</p>
<p><em>Now that&#8217;s something I hadn&#8217;t come across - that the current around a series circuit is limited to the sum of the resistances in the series&#8230;I&#8217;ll have to ponder that a bit more.   I always thought that if you had a specific voltage, you&#8217;d get a certain current.  And the only reason it slowed down temporarily would be because of a resistor, but then it&#8217;d pick right back up.</em></p>
<p>Oh, one more thing about current limiting in batteries: imagine that you  have a battery, and you just dead short the leads together with a wire  of no (or very little) resistance.   Let&#8217;s say it has a resistance of  0.001 ohm and the battery is a classic D cell with a nominal 1.5v  potential.   <br /><br />We know from Ohm&#8217;s law that E = I R, so 1.5 = I  0.001, or I = 1500 amps.  We also know that P = I E, so the wire would  be drawing about 2250 watts of power.    What usually happens in the  case of a small wire is that the wire glows and burns out.<br /><br />But  what if the wire was (say) a very thick copper bar?   Copper&#8217;s  resistance is very low (microohms per cm), and putting 2250 watts of  power into a bar several inches thick wouldn&#8217;t mean a lot&#8230;.<br /><br />Well,  what happens then is the batteries own internal or series resistance  comes into play.   Again, the voltage across the battery is 1.5 volts,  and now the copper bar and the batteries own internal resistance are in  series.   The batteries own resistance is usually a fraction of an ohm  (say 100 milliohms) which is is 1000x the resistance of the circuit.   This means that in reality, the battery absorbs the vast bulk of the  power, which is dissipated as heat.  And yes, that&#8217;s very bad for your  batteries.<br /><br />This is essentially how fuses protect circuits: when  the current through them exceeds a certain value, they burn out to keep  the high currents from damaging other components in series.</p>
<p><em>Neat :p.  I&#8217;m always a little scared of working too much with the formulas while I&#8217;m learning something new.  I like to make metaphors for the formulas instead of crunching numbers (though it&#8217;ll eventually be something I need to do obviously).</em></p>
<p><em>Many thanks for your comments!  Perhaps I&#8217;m making series vs parallel too complicated/adding too much drama to it :p.  But one day, a light bulb will go on and I&#8217;ll get it completely :)<br /></em></p></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
     title=""><a target="_blank" class="hover"
               title=""
               href="http://tymkrs.tumblr.com/post/3125276033/ponderings-re-comment"><div class="hover_inner"><span class="post_date">Feb 5, 2011</span></div>  

            <div class="hover_tags"></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3106517111"  data-post-id='3106517111' data-root-id='3106517111' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='3P3OJMs2' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.48659800 14060420251661281567' data-json='{"post-id":"3106517111","root-id":"3106517111","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"3P3OJMs2","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.48659800 14060420251661281567","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223106517111\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223106517111\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u00223P3OJMs2\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.48659800 14060420251661281567\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">Seventh Ham Lesson o&#039; de day</div><p>Circuits&#8230;.are like the jogging paths of the electrical world.    Currents flow through these circuits on their daily exercise regimen.    And if for instance you have light bulbs interspersed in that circuit so   that the electron joggers have to go through them, it is called a <strong>series circuit</strong>.</p>
<p>If two or more light bulbs are connected so that the same voltage is present across all of them, that is a <strong>parallel circuit</strong>.</p>
<p>[PAUSE] <em>I&#8217;d like to note that voltage and current is kinda like apples and oranges to me still. </em><em>Current  again measuring the number of electrons (coulombs/sec = amps) that  pass  through any given point per second, and Voltage being the electric   potential between two points. <br /></em></p>
<p><strong>Series Circuits</strong><em><br /></em></p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lffphnCKUT1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>This is a series circuit, where the &#8220;elements&#8221; are in a series -   Bulbs 1, 2, 3 - and the electrons only have one direction to travel in.    The current through each of these elements is the same but the voltage   is &#8220;shared&#8221; across each of the elements.  Assuming the light bulbs are   the same, the more light bulbs you add, the less voltage each light   bulbs gets to use:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lffw8m9WdJ1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>So  with one and two bulbs, 120volts are enough to light both  situations  up, but as soon as you add a third bulb, 40volts per light  bulb isn&#8217;t  enough to light them as brightly. <em> ﻿</em>Sometimes   people explain it as the amount of voltage decreasing each time the   current passes through an element (such as a light bulb), but I think   that ends up confusing people because then it sounds like each   subsequent light bulb should be dimmer and dimmer as the previous light   bulb sucks up the power it wants.  And that&#8217;s not how it works   apparently.﻿An example:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lffwirciLu1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>So  here, you have one bulb that requires more energy to light up.   The key  to understanding how this works is that POSITION DOES NOT  MATTER.  If  the 10watt bulb were in any other position, it&#8217;d still suck  up that much  power, and it&#8217;d still be the only one that was lit up.   At first this  confused me because I was like &#8220;Oh well, it&#8217;s the closest  to the power  source, so of course, it gets more power&#8221;, but that&#8217;s not  it at all,  it&#8217;s just relative to how much resistance it has - or how  much can it  prevent the current from moving on to the next element.</p>
<p>This is different when you&#8217;re hooking batteries up in series:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lffvixg2P41qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>So  here, the batteries are each worth 1.5V of power, and when you  place  them in series, with one of your voltmeter wires hooked to each  end of  the arrows - one wire on the yellow line and the other wire to  the green  line - you get the addition of those battery voltages to give  you 6V of  potential energy you can use to power a light bulb.  But the  current is  the same - the electrons still move as fast as they did when  they first  went into the loop.  A battery company online stated this: &#8220;A light bulb with this setup will burn very brightly, but for a short amount of time.&#8221;</p>
<p><strong>Parallel Circuits</strong></p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lffphfH45R1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>With this parallel circuit, the current gets split up among all of the potential paths but the voltage sent to each element stays the same.  Here, the 9V would be sent to the first, to the second, and to the third bulb in its entirety.</p>
<p><em><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lffz7wTa1D1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></em></p>
<p>No matter the number of lights/elements you add here, they will always receive the 120volts the power source says it&#8217;ll give.  <em>How is this accomplished?</em> Current (Amperage) from the  source increases each time another element is added to the circuit in  parallel. So, it&#8217;s very easy to keep adding elements in parallel and end up overloading a circuit by requiring more  current to flow than the circuit can safely handle. </p>
<p>Now let&#8217;s say the power supply isn&#8217;t from the wall, it&#8217;s from some piddly 9V battery.  <em>What happens when the amperage is more than the battery can handle? </em>Well&#8230;the battery gets hot and potentially damaged - I think is the general consensus&#8230;</p>
<p>And again this is different when looking at batteries in parallel:</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lffvqbOVTN1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>The battery company states: &#8220;A lightbulb with this set up will burn much less brightly but 4 times as long.&#8221;  So I guess here you have 4x the amount of current that provides 1.5 volts throughout.  As opposed to 1x the amount of current with 6 volts in one go. </p>
<p>MANY thanks to:</p>
<p><a href="http://smud.apogee.net/foe/fcsps.asp">http://smud.apogee.net/foe/fcsps.asp</a></p>
<p><a href="http://smud.apogee.net/foe/fcspp.asp">http://smud.apogee.net/foe/fcspp.asp</a></p>
<p>The two sites that helped me figure it out. </p>
