</div><div class="post post_micro is_photo post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3088340306"  data-post-id='3088340306' data-root-id='3088340306' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='YUm5ug9h' data-type='photo' data-serve-id='0.49641100 1406042025936708851' data-json='{"post-id":"3088340306","root-id":"3088340306","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"YUm5ug9h","type":"photo","serve-id":"0.49641100 1406042025936708851","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223088340306\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223088340306\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022YUm5ug9h\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022photo\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.49641100 1406042025936708851\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_thumbnail_container has_imageurl" style="height: 150px; width: 150px;" data-imageurl="http://31.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lg17xpmvgk1qffwoko1_250.jpg"></div></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
     title=""><a target="_blank" class="hover"
               title=""
               href="http://tymkrs.tumblr.com/post/3088340306/happy-chinese-new-year-this-is-the-year-of-the"><div class="hover_inner"><span class="post_date">Feb 3, 2011</span><span class="post_notes"
                        data-notes="1">1 note</span></div>  

            <div class="hover_tags"></div></a></div>
</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source has_hover" id="post_micro_3069263517"  data-post-id='3069263517' data-root-id='3069263517' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='AtBdbR3W' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.51002300 14060420251773402821' data-json='{"post-id":"3069263517","root-id":"3069263517","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"AtBdbR3W","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.51002300 14060420251773402821","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223069263517\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223069263517\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022AtBdbR3W\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.51002300 14060420251773402821\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">Gel Electrophoresis - Negative to Positive</div><p>So I wanted to show/explain a cool biological application to the idea of how negative voltages repel electrons and positive voltages attract them.</p>
<p>Gel electrophoresis is a method of separating out fragments of DNA, RNA, or even protein by BOTH size and charge.  This is done in a porous gel medium and involves an electrical current being run from negative to positive. </p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfew7aBmrF1qf00w4.gif" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>This works because DNA architecture, for example, includes a sugar-phosphate backbone which confers negative charge onto that particular DNA molecule.  This is shown here by the O-&#8230;&#8221;-&#8221; for negative charge.  And the gel itself is porous, meaning that there are different sized holes.  Molecules that are small enough can go through these holes - but! they need motivation, motivation in the form of an electrical current.</p>
<p>So, when you put an electrical current through: one end becoming negative and the other positive, molecules that are negative in charge will move towards the positive charge, but only up to a certain point. That point being their size.</p>
<p>The larger molecules get trapped closer to where they first entered the gel matrix, and the smaller molecules are able to move farther and faster along towards the positive pole of the gel.</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfevv8Z3tQ1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>Here&#8217;s an example of how it works - you have wells where you put your DNA samples + enzymes that break up the DNA at certain known points to make fragments.  And when you run a current through the gel, larger fragments get stuck behind whilst smaller fragments go farther along.  Usually, the lane on the left is the &#8220;reference&#8221; DNA - that is perhaps, the DNA found at the scene.  And the other lanes are suspects&#8217; DNA.  And what you do, is match up the bands between your suspects and the reference DNA, and bam! You find a match with Suspect 3!</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfexbsTdIr1qf00w4.jpg" alt="image" /></p></p>
<p>Did I mention it&#8217;s super fun to stick DNA into wells? It&#8217;s such a satisfying thing to be able to properly pipette colored DNA into a tiny space and see it settling.</p>
<p>Cool thing also is sometimes they use reference DNA with KNOWN numbers of DNA sizes - known as x number of base pairs.  So you can even find out through using gel electrophoresis how many base pairs an unknown DNA fragment has. As seen below! Those upper bands look like they&#8217;re about 410 base pairs and the lower bands look like they&#8217;re around 125 base pairs? Give or take anyway.</p>
<p><p><img class="toggle_inline_image inline_image constrained_image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lfexenPE9C1qf00w4.png" alt="image" /></p></p>

<p>@atdiy/@tymkrs</p></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
