</div><div class="post post_micro is_regular post_tumblelog_7652712883a78ee0a7e928bbd177f97e not_mine is_original with_permalink no_source no_notes has_hover" id="post_micro_3050190193"  data-post-id='3050190193' data-root-id='3050190193' data-tumblelog-name='tymkrs' data-tumblelog-key='PpptURJ1M' data-reblog-key='ANV5U53H' data-type='regular' data-serve-id='0.53322300 14060420251457475405' data-json='{"post-id":"3050190193","root-id":"3050190193","tumblelog-name":"tymkrs","tumblelog-key":"PpptURJ1M","reblog-key":"ANV5U53H","type":"regular","serve-id":"0.53322300 14060420251457475405","json":"{\u0022post-id\u0022:\u00223050190193\u0022,\u0022root-id\u0022:\u00223050190193\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-name\u0022:\u0022tymkrs\u0022,\u0022tumblelog-key\u0022:\u0022PpptURJ1M\u0022,\u0022reblog-key\u0022:\u0022ANV5U53H\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022regular\u0022,\u0022serve-id\u0022:\u00220.53322300 14060420251457475405\u0022}"}'><div class="post_content"><div class="post_content_inner"><div class="post_title">6.75 Ham lesson o&#039; de Day</div><p>Ground.  What&#8217;d I tell ya about this section taking a bit longer for me to understand :p. </p>
<p>According to the manual:</p>
<p>"The Earth&#8217;s surface acts as a universal reference for voltage measurements and is called earth ground, ground potential, or just ground."</p>
<p>What I understand about ground from just general life knowledge is that if lightning strikes your house, all of your appliances being  connected to ground (ie wire/pipes that actually go into the ground)  means that the electricity will try its damndest to get into the ground instead of into you or me. Path of least resistance essentially.</p>
<p>But my main questions have been:</p>
<p>1) What does it mean for ground to be a reference point for voltage measurements?</p>
<p>2) How do you measure ground with a multimeter&#8230;I mean, what&#8217;re you supposed to see?</p>
<p>From here the progression of thought has been as follows:</p>
<ul><li>Some explanations I&#8217;ve seen say that this provides a voltage level  against which all other voltages in a system are established and  measured.  <em>What&#8217;s its voltage level then?</em></li>
<li>(Tech-faq.com) Ground is a source of unlimited charge that remains at 0 volts. &#8220;It is the point from which all other potential differences in a circuit  are measured, and can be used as the return path for current in a  circuit.&#8221;  <em>So how do you measure that difference?</em></li>
<li>(epanorama.net) There are many sources of electricity. Every transformer can be considered a separate source. If there were not a common reference point for all these voltage sources it would be extremely difficult to calculate their relationships to each other. The earth is the most omnipresent conductive surface, and so it was adopted in the very beginnings as a nearly universal standard for all electric systems. </li>
<li>(UPenn) Early developers of electrical systems theorized that the earth was an electrically neutral body, i.e. an equal number of negative and positive charges are distributed throughout the earth at any given time. Being electrically neutral, earth is considered to be at zero potential and establishes a convenient reference frame for voltage measurements. Noting that voltmeters read only the difference in potential between two points, absolute measurements can be made by using earth as a reference. </li>
<li>(@whixr) If everything in the world had a slight negative charge, you&#8217;d think that was considered a Zero voltage, but when you have a reference point that actually does not have a potential, you can tell that these are actually slightly negative, or whatever. </li>
</ul><p>I kinda understand it now. Hopefully you do too, but let me know if I need to come up with some wacky sort of metaphor to get it rolling.</p>
<ul></ul><p>@atdiy/@tymkrs</p></div></div><div class="post_glass post_micro_glass" 
